<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+[Critique]&nbsp;Click&nbsp;to&nbsp;Access</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">-[Click&nbsp;to&nbsp;Hide&nbsp;Text]</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>I so badly want to like this article. I want to upvote this. But I can't bring myself to.</p>
<p>Echoing from what Chandra said, I don't think real-world problems would have the same weight that they do on the rest of the world. They just seem so minor compared to the work the Foundation is doing, especially when many articles make the Foundation out to having a <em>lot</em> of weight to throw around. It's also weird to see such things affect Wondertainment as a company.</p>
<p>But I get it. The Wonder World!™ canon is about taking in real-life for what it is. It's about realizing that there comes a day when you can't be a child anymore and your actions have meaning and you have to grow up or the world rejects you. And this really hits that in how Holly rants for<em>ever</em> about how little hope she has left and how much of a burden looking at the world outside of Wonder World!™ is. I get it. The world is unfriendly and there's only so much magic can do. I didn't need Holly talking for half of the skip to get that information, but I understand.</p>
<p>Normally, I would upvote on the sentiments presented alone because that's <em>heartbreaking</em> and I'm really feeling that, but Wondertainment giving in is such a jarring thing to see. I find it incredibly hard to believe that they would settle for working with the Foundation, and I find it even more unlikely that the Foundation would give Wondertainment the time of day and compromise on manufacturing their toys.</p>
<p>I want to like this, but I'm conflicted. So this is a no-vote.</p>
</div>
